\begin{abstract}
This paper presents a repository-based analysis of a landmark-driven Indian Sign Language recognition system that converts short video clips into sequence-level gesture predictions. The implemented pipeline uses MediaPipe hand and face landmark extraction, face-relative normalization, temporal velocity encoding, and a bidirectional GRU classifier with proximity-biased attention. The active configuration processes 20 frames per sample and represents each frame with 253 features, yielding a 506-dimensional input sequence after velocity augmentation. The repository contains 42 active classes, 5,683 processed landmark sequences, and both online and offline augmentation utilities, including Gaussian noise, scaling, rotation, temporal shifts, frame dropout, time warping, mixup, and sequence-merging strategies. On the current validation split, the single checkpoint achieves 92.68\% accuracy with 93.42\% macro precision, 92.84\% macro recall, and 92.94\% macro F1-score. The repository README additionally reports a 5-fold ensemble mean accuracy of 95.83\%. These results indicate that augmentation-aware training, class balancing, and temporal attention jointly improve recognition robustness on an imbalanced, signer-dependent landmark dataset.
\end{abstract}

