\section{Introduction}
Landmark-based sign language recognition is challenging because hand configurations, motion trajectories, and signer-to-signer variation can produce highly overlapping temporal patterns. The analyzed repository addresses this problem using a compact landmark representation rather than raw RGB frames, reducing the input burden while preserving the motion cues needed for word-level recognition.

The project focuses on Indian Sign Language word classification from short video clips. Its principal contribution is not a novel sensor modality, but a layered engineering pipeline: MediaPipe-based hand and face extraction, face-relative normalization, temporal velocity features, data augmentation at both sequence and training time, and a BiGRU classifier with proximity-aware attention. The repository also includes K-fold ensemble inference and temporal smoothing for real-time use.

This study derives its analysis directly from the implementation and experimental results available in the repository. Where a direct ablation is absent, the limitation is stated rather than inferred.

\section{Related Work}
Sign language recognition has been extensively explored using both vision-based and sensor-based approaches. Early methods relied on convolutional neural networks applied to RGB video frames, which require large-scale datasets and significant computational resources. More recent work leverages landmark-based representations using frameworks such as MediaPipe, which provide a compact and efficient alternative by encoding hand and pose geometry.

Temporal modeling plays a critical role in gesture recognition. Recurrent neural networks, particularly Long Short-Term Memory (LSTM) and Gated Recurrent Unit (GRU) architectures, have been widely used to capture sequential dependencies in sign language data. Transformer-based approaches have also gained attention for modeling long-range temporal relationships.

Data augmentation has been identified as a key technique for improving generalization, especially in low-resource settings. While augmentation is well studied in image space, fewer works systematically analyze augmentation strategies applied directly to landmark sequences. This paper focuses on evaluating such augmentation techniques within a complete landmark-based recognition pipeline.

