\section{Contributions and Novelty}
We summarize the concrete, non-generic contributions of this work. Each item below highlights what differs from a standard landmark-based sign language pipeline and what is reproducible from the repository.

\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Structured landmark representation with explicit proximity and velocity:} We use a compact 506-dimensional per-frame representation that concatenates raw 3D hand landmarks, face-relative hand coordinates, an explicit hand-to-face proximity scalar, and frame-to-frame velocity. This combination exposes hand–face interactions and short-term dynamics to the temporal model without relying on raw RGB cues.

\item \textbf{Proximity-biased hybrid attention:} The model implements a multi-head temporal attention mechanism that incorporates a learnable Gaussian proximity prior and per-head temperature parameters. This biases attention toward temporally and spatially relevant frames (e.g., when hands are near the face), improving discriminability for face-referenced signs.

\item \textbf{Merge-based offline augmentation suite:} Beyond standard jittering and time-warping, the repository provides a set of synthetic sequence generators (frame-splice, weighted-blend, hand-swap, and hybrid merges) that produce realistic intra-class temporal variants. These generators are explicitly designed and parameterized for landmark sequences rather than image pixels.

\item \textbf{Multi-level augmentation + balancing strategy:} The pipeline integrates stochastic online sequence augmentations (noise, scaling, rotation, dropout, time-warp), offline merge generators, Mixup, label smoothing, inverse-frequency class weighting, and oversampling. The combined, layered strategy is targeted at small, imbalanced landmark datasets and is presented with reproducible code and hyperparameters.

\item \textbf{Practical, lightweight evaluation protocol:} We document a reproducible evaluation path that combines a compact BiGRU backbone (under 1M parameters), stratified k-fold training, ensemble averaging with test-time augmentation, and per-class reporting. This makes it straightforward to reproduce performance gains while keeping compute requirements modest.

\item \textbf{Reproducible ablation framework:} The codebase includes hooks and configuration toggles that allow controlled ablations (disable augmentation families, remove velocity or face-relative inputs, disable attention). We leverage these to quantify the contribution of each engineering component.
\end{itemize}

\section{Methodology}

\subsection{System Pipeline}
The end-to-end pipeline is:
\begin{enumerate}
\item Raw videos are stored under \texttt{Dataset/} in class-specific folders.
\item \texttt{preprocess.py} samples 20 frames per clip, crops frames to 640$\times$480, and extracts MediaPipe hand and face landmarks.
\item Each frame is converted into a fixed-length feature vector and stored as a \texttt{.npy} sequence in \texttt{processed/}.
\item \texttt{dataset.py} loads the sequences, applies training augmentation, and optionally oversamples minority classes.
\item \texttt{train.py} trains a BiGRU classifier with weighted cross-entropy, label smoothing, early stopping, and learning-rate scheduling.
\item \texttt{ensemble.py} loads fold checkpoints and performs test-time augmentation during inference.
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Landmark Representation}
The active configuration uses 21 MediaPipe hand landmarks per hand with $(x,y,z)$ coordinates. Raw hand features are concatenated for both hands:
\[
D_{\text{raw}} = 21 \times 3 \times 2 = 126.
\]
The preprocessing stage also computes face-relative hand coordinates using a face anchor derived from the nose and eye landmarks. This produces another 126 features per frame. A proximity scalar is appended to indicate hand-to-face distance:
\[
D_{\text{frame}} = 126 + 126 + 1 = 253.
\]
Because velocity is enabled, the input sequence concatenates position and frame-to-frame deltas:
\[
D_{\text{seq}} = 2 \times 253 = 506.
\]
The active configuration therefore uses 20-frame sequences of shape $(20, 506)$. Although the configuration contains optional spatial-distance features, they are disabled in the current run, so they do not contribute to the reported input size.

\subsection{Data Augmentation Techniques}
The repository implements augmentation at three levels.

\subsubsection{Sequence-Level Augmentation During Training}
The dataset wrapper applies the following stochastic operations:
\begin{itemize}
\item Gaussian noise injection on landmark coordinates.
\item Random scaling to simulate distance variation.
\item Temporal shift via frame rolling.
\item Random frame dropout.
\item Small XY rotation of raw hand landmarks.
\item Time warping by resampling frames.
\item Per-hand dropout to simulate partial occlusion.
\item Stronger frame-specific noise for corrupted segments.
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Offline Synthetic Sequence Augmentation}
Separate augmentation scripts create additional landmark sequences using:
\begin{itemize}
\item Temporal speed variation.
\item Spatial noise injection.
\item Random translation.
\item Random scaling around the wrist or frame mean.
\item Frame drop and interpolation.
\item Frame-splice merge.
\item Weighted blend merge.
\item Hand-swap merge.
\item Hybrid merge combinations.
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Training-Time Regularization}
The training loop additionally uses Mixup with $\alpha = 0.3$ and probability 0.5. Inference uses a light test-time augmentation scheme with small Gaussian noise and mild scaling.

