\subsection{Model Architecture}
The classifier is a bidirectional GRU with attention. The active configuration uses:
\begin{itemize}
\item Input projection: 506 $\rightarrow$ 128.
\item A 3-layer bidirectional GRU with hidden size 128 and dropout 0.35.
\item Hybrid attention with multiple heads and a Gaussian proximity prior.
\item A spatial attention block over feature groups.
\item A fully connected head of 256 $\rightarrow$ 96 $\rightarrow$ 42 classes.
\end{itemize}

The resulting model contains 992,976 trainable parameters. Class outputs correspond to the 42 active processed classes.

\section{Experimental Setup}

\subsection{Dataset Details}
The repository contains 528 raw videos distributed across 42 class folders in \texttt{Dataset/}. Preprocessing converts these clips into 5,683 landmark sequences in \texttt{processed/}. Of these, 1,903 are original processed sequences and 3,780 are augmented derivatives identified by filename patterns such as \texttt{\_aug\_}, \texttt{\_merge\_}, and \texttt{\_mrg\_}.

The dataset is mildly imbalanced. For example, the largest processed classes include \texttt{ugly} (165 samples), \texttt{beautiful} (155), and \texttt{you} (150), while the smallest include \texttt{thin} (120) and \texttt{poor} (125). The training split is therefore balanced by oversampling.

\subsection{Train-Validation Split}
The repository uses a stratified random split with \texttt{val\_split = 0.25}. No subject-independent partition is defined in the code, so the split is sample-stratified rather than signer-disjoint. In the current run, the split produced 4,262 training samples and 1,421 validation samples before oversampling. Balanced augmentation expanded the training subset to 5,208 samples, with 124 examples per class after oversampling.

\subsection{Training Hyperparameters}
The current configuration uses:
\begin{itemize}
\item Batch size: 16
\item Learning rate: $3 \times 10^{-4}$
\item Weight decay: $5 \times 10^{-4}$
\item Epochs: 60
\item Early stopping patience: 10
\item Scheduler: ReduceLROnPlateau for the single model
\item Label smoothing: 0.05
\item Class weighting: inverse-frequency weighting
\item Gradient clipping: 1.0
\end{itemize}

The K-fold training path uses 5 stratified folds and cosine warm restarts. Focal loss and CutMix are available in the code but disabled in the captured configuration.

\subsection{Evaluation Metrics}
The repository explicitly supports accuracy and per-class accuracy reporting. For the paper, standard macro-averaged precision, recall, and F1-score are also reported from the current validation run. A confusion matrix is natural for this setup because the classifier is multi-class with 42 labels. The repository does not persist a no-augmentation ablation, so that comparison is not tabulated numerically.

