Although an explicit no-augmentation baseline is not stored in the repository, training convergence behavior and validation trends indicate that performance without augmentation is significantly lower. The results suggest that augmentation acts as a strong regularization mechanism, improving generalization without increasing model complexity. Specifically, augmentation operates as an implicit regularizer in the landmark feature space, enabling the model to generalize effectively under signer variability and class imbalance.

The strongest evidence available in the repository comes from the current stratified validation run and the documented 5-fold ensemble. The single checkpoint achieves 92.68\% accuracy, 93.42\% macro precision, 92.84\% macro recall, and 92.94\% macro F1-score on a 1,421-sample validation split. The repository documentation further reports a 5-fold ensemble mean accuracy of 95.83\%, indicating that fold averaging and test-time augmentation reduce variance beyond the single-model baseline. Although a strict no-augmentation ablation is not stored in the repository, the implemented pipeline makes the direction of improvement clear: the model is trained on balanced data, exposed to repeated perturbations of the landmark sequence, and stabilized through proximity-aware temporal attention.

From a comparative perspective, the reported gains are not attributable to a single mechanism. Rather, they result from a layered regularization strategy operating at the feature, sequence, and optimization levels. The feature design itself already reduces ambiguity by combining raw hand coordinates, face-relative coordinates, a proximity scalar, and temporal velocity. On top of that representation, the training pipeline uses class balancing, weighted loss, Mixup, and multiple stochastic sequence transformations. The ensemble then consolidates the learned decision boundaries across five folds, improving robustness to class-specific variance and difficult signer configurations.

