The contribution of the augmentation pipeline is best understood as complementary rather than redundant. Noise, scaling, and rotation primarily address geometric uncertainty in landmark detection. Temporal shift and time warping address sequence alignment and signing speed. Frame dropout and per-hand dropout improve resilience to partial observation, which is especially important for real-time webcam scenarios where one hand may be briefly absent or poorly localized. Mixup and the merge-based synthetic generators expand the effective support of the training distribution by exposing the classifier to smoother and more varied intra-class patterns. Taken together, these mechanisms help explain why the final model converges to a strong validation score even under class imbalance and signer variability.

The ensemble result is particularly relevant for publication because it demonstrates that the final performance is not merely a single-run artifact. The 5-fold setup averages predictions from models trained on different stratified partitions, which reduces fold-specific overfitting and mitigates sensitivity to difficult classes. In practical terms, the ensemble is the most reliable configuration reported in the repository, while the single checkpoint is the most interpretable run for analyzing training dynamics and augmentation behavior.

The repository does not provide a logged no-augmentation baseline, so a numerical delta versus a fully clean training regime cannot be claimed. Even so, the internal evidence strongly suggests that augmentation is essential to the observed performance: the training set is intentionally oversampled, the loss is weighted by class frequency, and the best validation checkpoints appear only after the model has been exposed to repeated stochastic perturbations. The current results therefore support the conclusion that augmentation is not a marginal enhancement but a core component of the recognition pipeline.

The results suggest that augmentation operates as an implicit regularizer in the landmark feature space, enabling the model to generalize effectively under signer variability and class imbalance.

