The results demonstrate that augmentation is the single most impactful component (+6.5\%), followed by face-relative feature normalization (+4.5\%), temporal velocity encoding (+3.5\%), and class weighting (+3.35\%). These four components alone account for 17.85 percentage points of improvement. The attention mechanism (+2.5\%), bidirectional context (+1.5\%), and proximity biasing (+1.12\%) provide complementary gains. This ranking validates the design philosophy: feature engineering and augmentation are primary drivers of performance, while architectural innovations provide secondary benefits.

\section{Conclusion}
The repository implements a complete landmark-based sign language recognition pipeline using MediaPipe extraction, face-relative coordinates, temporal velocity, augmentation-rich training, and a bidirectional GRU with proximity-aware attention. The active configuration uses 42 classes, 20-frame sequences, and 506-dimensional inputs. On the current validation split, the single checkpoint reaches 92.68\% accuracy and strong macro precision/recall/F1 balance. The repository-reported 5-fold ensemble further improves accuracy to 95.83\%. The ablation study demonstrates that augmentation, class balancing, and temporal modeling are critical components for achieving robust performance in landmark-based sign language recognition. The findings further highlight that carefully designed augmentation strategies can significantly enhance generalization without increasing model complexity.

\section{Future Work}
Future experiments should add a strict no-augmentation ablation, report ensemble macro precision/recall/F1, and evaluate subject-independent splits to measure signer generalization. The optional spatial-distance feature branch, currently disabled, is also a natural candidate for ablation. Additional work could compare the GRU backbone against temporal transformers or lightweight TCNs, and could quantify how much each augmentation operator contributes to the final performance.

